subSubSection.paragraph:
Eyes relatively large as compared to orbital space; eyestalk short, narrow, laterally concave; cornea large, pigmented (
Fig. 9B
).

Antennules long, folded in longitudinally broad fossae; antennae distally deformed but still long, equal in length to eyestalk (
Fig. 9B, C
). Mandibular palp 2-segmented; terminal segment bilobed. First, second maxillipeds each with long flagellum on exopod (
Fig. 9C
). Third maxillipeds cover most of buccal cavity when closed; ischium subrectangular, longer than broad, with deep, oblique submedial groove; merus subrectangular, broader than long, sunken; exopod moderately stout, distally narrow, longer than ischium, reaching proximal half of merus, with well-developed flagellum (
Fig. 9B–D
).

Carapace, chelipeds and ambulatory legs all are brown with numerous purplish-brown spots on the dorsal surface (
Fig. 13
). Their ventral surfaces are paler and spotless.

